   series = {COSPAR Meeting},
   volume = 40,
 abstract = "{PoGOLite is a balloon-borne hard X-ray polarimeter. It determines
polarisation by measuring the azimuthal distribution of Compton
scattered photons in a plastic scintillator array. The dominant source
of background for these measurements has been shown through Geant4
simulations to originate from high energy (MeV range) atmospheric
neutrons produced in cosmic ray induced air showers. PoGOLite was
launched in July 2013 from the Esrange Space Centre in Northern Sweden,
drifted westwards for 15 days at an altitude of 40 km and landed near
Norilsk in Russia. Due to the low geomagnetic cutoff at which the flight
took place, the neutron background is relatively high. At these
latitudes the flux is also sensitive to changes in Solar activity. As a
result the polarimeter experiences a continuously changing neutron flux
during flight. The continuous variation of the induced background and
the lack of data on the neutron flux in the high altitude / high
latitude region motivates the need for a dedicated neutron detector on
the payload. For this purpose PoGOLite makes use of a scintillator based
neutron detector capable of measuring in the high radiation environment
experienced at stratospheric altitudes. This type of neutron detector
was tested on a separate dedicated stratospheric balloon mission, called
PoGOLino, in March 2013. The flight results from both instruments were
compared to predictions from a Monte Carlo based model developed to
provide atmospheric neutron spectra for different altitudes, magnetic
latitudes and solar activities. The flight results from both detectors
will be presented together with the predictions from the model.
